<span class="pill">SAFE SLEEP</span>
<h1>When Can Baby Sleep With a Blanket? NHS Guidance</h1>
<p class="subtitle">The answer is 12 months minimum – here's the safer alternative UK parents use.</p>
<div class="meta">Written by Mark, Belfast dad • Checked against NHS and Lullaby Trust • Last updated 16 April 2026</div>

<div class="warning">
<p><strong>NHS guidance:</strong> No blankets, duvets, quilts or pillows for babies under 12 months. Use a baby sleep bag instead.</p>
</div>

<p>Our health visitor in Belfast was blunt: "blankets kill babies". Harsh, but true – loose bedding is a major SIDS risk factor. UK guidance is crystal clear, yet John Lewis still sells "newborn blanket sets". Don't use them for sleep.</p>

<h2>Why blankets are dangerous under 12 months</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Suffocation:</strong> Baby wriggles, blanket covers face, can't push it away until 9-12 months</li>
<li><strong>Overheating:</strong> Blankets trap heat, can't be kicked off reliably. Overheating increases SIDS risk 4x according to Lullaby Trust data</li>
<li><strong>Entanglement:</strong> Limbs get wrapped, baby can't free themselves</li>
<li><strong>Inconsistent warmth:</strong> Blanket falls off, baby gets cold, wakes crying</li>
</ul>
<p>Even "cellular blankets" with holes – marketed as safer – are not recommended by NHS under 12 months. The holes don't prevent suffocation risk.</p>

<h2>What age is safe?</h2>
<p><strong>12 months:</strong> Absolute minimum, and only if baby can roll both ways, sit up, and pull blanket off face deliberately.</p>
<p><strong>18 months+:</strong> Safer age. Most UK parents wait until toddler bed transition.</p>
<p><strong>Our experience:</strong> We introduced a light cellular blanket at 20 months, over sleep bag in winter. Baby could pull it off and ask for it back – that's the test of readiness.</p>

<h2>What to use instead – sleep bags</h2>
<p>NHS specifically recommends baby sleep bags (also called baby sleeping bags or grobags). Benefits:</p>
<ul>
<li>Can't cover face</li>
<li>Consistent warmth all night</li>
<li>Correct TOG for room temperature – see our <a href="/posts/tog-ratings-made-simple.html">TOG guide</a></li>
<li>Baby can't kick off and get cold</li>
<li>Reduces risk of climbing out of cot later</li>
</ul>
<p>We used 2.5 TOG in winter (room 16-18°C), 1.0 TOG spring/autumn, 0.5 TOG summer. One sleep bag replaces blanket, sheet, and worry.</p>

<h2>But my baby hates sleep bags?</h2>
<p>Try different style – some have arms, some are sleeveless. Ensure correct size (not too big). Put baby in sleep bag for daytime naps first to get used to it. Swaddle transition bags help for babies moving from swaddle. Persistence pays off – it's safer.</p>

<h2>What about swaddling with blankets?</h2>
<p>NHS says if you swaddle, use thin cotton muslin, stop by 2-3 months or when signs of rolling. Never swaddle over 3 months, never with blanket over top, never with baby on front. We stopped swaddling at 8 weeks and moved straight to sleep bag – easier transition.</p>

<h2>Grandparents insisting on blankets?</h2>
<p>Common in UK – "you slept with blankets and survived". Show them current Lullaby Trust guidance. SIDS rates dropped 80% since Back to Sleep campaign in 1991, largely due to removing loose bedding. It's not worth the risk for tradition.</p>

<h2>When you do introduce a blanket</h2>
<p>At 12-18 months: use light cellular blanket only, tucked in firmly at foot of bed no higher than chest, baby's feet to foot of cot. Better still, continue sleep bag until 2-3 years then move to blanket and duvet together when in bed.</p>

<h2>Room temperature matters more</h2>
<p>Parents use blankets because room is cold. Fix the room, not the bedding. Keep room 16-20°C, use correct TOG sleep bag. See our <a href="/posts/room-temperature-baby-nhs.html">room temperature guide</a>.</p>

